50|$|UN Chief Inspector Hans Blix, on 14 February 2003, {{presented}} {{a report to}} the Security Council. Blix gave an update of the situation in Iraq, and he stated <b>that</b> <b>the</b> <b>Iraqis</b> were now more proactive in their cooperation. He also rebutted some of the arguments proposed by Powell. Blix questioned the interpretations of the satellite images put forward by Powell, and stated that alternate interpretations of the satellite images were credible. He also stated <b>that</b> <b>the</b> <b>Iraqis</b> have in fact never received early warning of the inspectors visiting any sites (an allegation made by Powell during his presentation). International Atomic Energy Agency Director General Mohammed ElBaradei also said that he did not believe <b>the</b> <b>Iraqis</b> have a nuclear weapons program, unlike what Powell had claimed.|$|R
